The '''red complex''' is a group of [[bacteria]] that are categorized together based on their association with severe forms of [[periodontal disease]].<ref name=pmid11312465>{{cite journal |doi=10.1067/moe.2001.114379 |pmid=11312465 |title='Red complex' (Bacteroides forsythus, Porphyromonas gingivalis, and Treponema denticola ) in endodontic infections: A molecular approach |journal=Oral Surgery, Oral Medicine, Oral Pathology, Oral Radiology, and Endodontology |volume=91 |issue=4 |pages=468–71 |year=2001 |last1=Rôças |first1=Isabela N |last2=Siqueira |first2=José F |last3=Santos |first3=Kátia R.N |last4=Coelho |first4=Ana M.A |last5=De Janeiro |first5=Rio }}</ref> The red complex—among a number of other [[species complex|complex]]es—were classified by [[Sigmund Socransky]] in 1998.<ref>Wolf, Herbert F.; Rateitschak, Klaus. ''Color Atlas of Dental Medicine: Periodontology'', 3rd Edition, Thieme 2005, {{ISBN|0-86577-902-3}} page 37.</ref>

The three members of the red complex are:
# ''[[Porphyromonas gingivalis]]''
# ''[[Tannerella forsythia]]''
# ''[[Treponema denticola]]''

